\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 Put the grits in a large bowl, fill with water and stir. Let the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/grits/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 grits}} stand for about 5 minutes for the bran to rise to the surface; pour off the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/bran/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 bran}} and excess water and set aside.\
Bring the stock and half-and-half to a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/boil/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 boil}}, over high heat, in a medium heavy-bottomed pan and slowly {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/whisk/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 whisk}} in the grits. Reduce the heat to medium-low and cook, stirring often, until thick and creamy, about 45 minutes. If the grits get too thick, stir in additional hot stock or water to loosen and thin.\
Add the Gruyere and the bacon {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/drippings/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 drippings}}, if using, and stir until the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cheese/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cheese}} melts. Season with salt and pepper, to taste. Transfer to a serving bowl and serve immediately.}